# Client_Server_ACW

This is the completed version of **002_CWRK: Networking and UID Coursework**.
When first running the client and server you first need to run the server from Visual Studio with ***-w*** in the Debug properties or by inputting ***locationserver -w*** in the command prompt.
Though the server did not pass all the tests in Lab4, it is able to complete the tasks with the same inputs as the Lab4Test.
Below is a list of labs that had to be completed in order to achieve ad fully running client and server and a step by step instruction on how to run the softwares.

## How to run the Client & Server:

1. Start *locationserver* from Visual Studio or Command Prompt.
2. Press **Start Server** Button. 
   - This will make the server start listening.
3. Start *location* from Visual Studio or Command Prompt.
4. Enter any variables you may wish to use.
5. Enjoy

## Coursework Step by Step:

- ![#c5f015](https://via.placeholder.com/15/c5f015/000000?text=+) `Complete`
- ![##ffd966](https://via.placeholder.com/15/ffd966/000000?text=+) `Incomplete`
- ![#f03c15](https://via.placeholder.com/15/f03c15/000000?text=+) `No attempt`

- ![#c5f015](https://via.placeholder.com/15/c5f015/000000?text=+) Step 0. The first practical task introduced you to the sample client used in the lectures. You 
may need to check about the method stream.flush which is not included in the example code. 
```diff
+ No issues with Lab 0.
```

- ![#c5f015](https://via.placeholder.com/15/c5f015/000000?text=+) Step 1. Develop and complete your client to perform a whois request by having it communicate 
with the working server provided by your lecturer ( whois.net.dcs.hull.ac.uk) or an external 
third party internet whois server. This should be based on the code template given in the lecture 
Powerpoint. It is often sensible to be sure of the correctness of your client before proceeding to 
develop your server. It might be a good idea to start using source control such as GIT or the 
SVN server to keep track of the development of your solution (depending on which you have 
been using on the course). 
```diff
+ No issues with Lab 1.
```

- ![#c5f015](https://via.placeholder.com/15/c5f015/000000?text=+) Step 2. Develop a minimal server based on the template in the Powerpoint slides that uses the 
whois protocol, using your own client to interface with it. You would need to write code to 
store the person locations in the server memory, and you might find the classes 
for Hashtable or Dictionary particularly useful for this. We suggest that you initially develop 
a server that does not use threads, to ensure the protocol and communications work properly. 
This can then be augmented to handle multiple clients and multiple protocols later. 
```diff
+ No issues with Lab 2.
```

- ![#c5f015](https://via.placeholder.com/15/c5f015/000000?text=+) Step 3. Extend your basic working client to include the command line arguments of -h, -p. 
Add the HTTP protocols incrementally and the arguments -h0, -h1, -h9 and test against a 
web server. 
```diff
+ No issue with Lab 3
```

- ![#c5f015](https://via.placeholder.com/15/c5f015/000000?text=+) Step 4. Extend your basic server to recognise HTTP protocol requests and test with your client 
and later with a web browser. You should also do this incrementally adding one protocol at a 
time. 
```diff
+ Server runs with no issues when using the client.
! Lab 4 was showing advisories for HTTP 1.1 and HTTP 1.0 update and updated lookup, these errors were not found when using the Client.
! Server needs to be started by either starting it from Visual Studios or by entering "locationserver -w" in the Command Prompt.
```

- ![#c5f015](https://via.placeholder.com/15/c5f015/000000?text=+) Step 5. Upgrade your server to include handling of multiple threads so concurrent enquiries 
from multiple clients is possible. If you find this difficult to achieve, remember to retain a copy 
of your working non-threaded server to hand-in for assessment should you not have a working 
threaded version. Do not damage your only working server when trying to add more capability, 
or you risk losing all the marks you earned to this point. You might find that using GIT or SVN 
from the first week has become valuable is assisting you in recovering earlier versions!  
```diff
+ No issues with Lab 5, able to run with 1000 clients.
```

- ![##ffd966](https://via.placeholder.com/15/ffd966/000000?text=+) (Optional) Step 6. Add any remaining optional features to your client and server, such as logging, and 
finish testing. Now prepare to add user interface features to the client and server for part2.

```diff
+ User Interface using WPF has been integrated.
! Server UI only allows the user to start the Server.
! Server UI will not show the Logging, this is done in the background and only visible through the Command Prompt that opens when running the server.
! Logging is implemented.
```
